# Introduction
![bg right:40%](assets/images/new_year_background.jpg)

- Japanese New Year (お正月) is the most important holiday in Japan
- Traditional customs date back centuries
- Celebration period: December 31st - January 3rd
- Time for family gatherings and traditional activities

---

# Shishimai (Lion Dance)
![bg right:40%](assets/images/shishimai.png)

- Traditional performance to ward off evil spirits
- Brings good luck for the new year
- Performed at shrines and temples
- Features a lion-like mask and colorful costume
- Often accompanied by traditional music

---

# Kadomatsu (Gate Pine)
![bg right:40%](assets/images/kadomatsu.png)

- Traditional decoration placed at entrances
- Made of bamboo, pine, and plum branches
- Welcomes ancestral spirits and deities
- Symbolizes longevity and prosperity
- Displayed from December 28th until January 7th

---

# Kagami Mochi (Mirror Rice Cake)
![bg right:40%](assets/images/kagami_mochi_1.png)

- Two-tiered round rice cakes
- Topped with a bitter orange (daidai)
- Symbol of the year's reflection
- Traditional offering to gods
- Displayed until January 11th

---

# Otoshidama (New Year's Gift Money)
![bg right:40%](assets/images/otoshidama.png)

- Money gifts given to children
- Presented in special envelopes
- Amount varies by age
- Important family tradition
- Teaches financial responsibility

---

# Conclusion
![bg right:40%](assets/images/new_year_background.jpg)

- Rich cultural traditions
- Family-centered celebrations
- Blend of religious and secular customs
- Important part of Japanese identity
- Continues to evolve while preserving tradition